# Nested at a moderate width where the outer list's body cannot
# fit on its indented line but the inner list's body can. The
# per-level [docBodyShape] decision yields a mixed cascade: the
# hug shape at the outer level (cells force-broken, brackets hug
# the edges), the indented shape at the inner level (brackets on
# their own lines with the body inline at indent+1).
#
# Budget analysis at width 24:
#   - outer flat: `x: [[{a: _}, {b: _}], {c: _}]` = 28 > 24 -> outer
#     list's group broken.
#   - outer body flat at indent+1 (1 tab = 4 cols): need to fit in
#     `24 - 4 = 20` cols; body = `[{a:_}, {b:_}], {c:_}` (21) does
#     not fit -> outer bodyShape picks the hug shape.
#   - inner is force-broken via its [docNextGroupNoop] wrapping;
#     inner's own list's group breaks. Inner body flat at indent+1
#     (also 4 cols here, since the outer hug shape leaves the
#     inner at the outer's caller indent): `{a:_}, {b:_}` = 14 <= 20
#     -> inner bodyShape picks the indented shape.
#   - outer struct `{c:_}` is force-broken too; its body is small
#     but the NextGroupNoop wrapper still forces multi-line.
#
# The indented shape's trailing comma on `{b: _}` is what makes the
# output idempotent: the re-parsed AST has `Rbrack.RelPos == Newline`,
# which makes the standard layout add a trailing comma on re-render,
# matching the first render.
-- config --
width: 24
-- in.cue --
x: [[{a: _}, {b: _}], {c: _}]
-- out/relpos --
x: [[{a: _}, {b: _}], {c: _}]
-- out/norelpos --
x: [[
	{a: _}, {b: _},
], {
	c: _
}]
